Footage shows the moment the device hits the walls of the fortified Government building. Following this, small fires can be seen at the base of its walls. Putin is understood to have lived in the Grand Kremlin Palace since last year. It is historically the site at which the Russian leader also undergoes their business. The video posted on social media has also been shared on local media outlets, according to the Star. Given the positioning of the explosive launches on the outer walls of the Kremlin, the act was unlikely an attempt at assassination but a demonstration, presumably against the invasion of Ukraine. Putin has, however, faced numerous assassination attempts in the past. READ MORE: Russia’s Lavrov admits Moscow wasn't prepared for sanctions Asked about this by US documentary maker Oliver Stone in 2017, the Russian President expressed little sign of worry. Instead, he told of a Russian saying: “They say that those who are destined to be hanged are not going to drown.” Putin added: “Only God knows our destiny – yours and mine.” DON'T MISS: Zelensky’s call for no fly zone rejected [OPINION] Putin's army from 'mysteriously weak' to 'brutal' [REVEAL] People sensationally blame Brexit for Russia's chilling invasion [REPORT] The demonstration outside the Kremlin came amid increasing pressure on Russia as a result of Western sanctions. Russian Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov today, on Wednesday, admitted Moscow was not prepared for the "thievery" of sanctions imposed following the invasion of Ukraine. He said: “When they [froze] the central bank reserves, nobody who was predicting what sanctions the West would pass could have pictured that. It's just thievery.” Anatoly Chubais’s reported departure has been touted as the “highest-level official to break with the Kremlin over the invasion” to date. It is possible this could boost the confidence of other Russian officials sceptical of the ongoing action in Ukraine to make their positions clear.